  "text": "In addition, several lines of evidence suggest that the D 2 R (and to a lesser extent the D 3 R) can also act through a G protein-independent pathway to increase glycogen synthase kinase-3 (GSK-3) activity, via a complex consisting of b-arrestin 2, protein kinase B (Akt), and protein phosphatase 2A (PP2A) [CITATION_1] (Beaulieu et al. ,b, 2009 . In this pathway, PP2A dephosphorylates and deactivates the kinase Akt, thereby enabling the subsequent dephosphorylation and activation of GSK-3 (for a review, see [CITATION_2] . It has been hypothesized that hyperactivation of GSK-3 is involved in both bipolar disorder [CITATION_3] and schizophrenia [CITATION_4] .",
